text: I was a black kid in the ghetto in the 90s, and absolutely no one understood me the way The Smashing Pumpkins did. I can relate to being young and hearing music outside of your culture that speaks to *YOU* the way no one within your own familial/cultural bubble possibly can.      But hey, that was when *I felt like a rat in a cage* . But now *I've woke up from that sleep and I'm happier, than I've ever been* . I sometimes go back to my old town, *and in the same old haunts I still find my friends* , and *the streets still heat the urgency of now* . And despite it all, *underneath the wheels lie the skulls of every cog, the fickle fascination of an everlasting God*

text: I'm a Hispanic who grew up in the United States. Born and raised in the midwest to Hispanic parents who wanted me to learn English first so as to not struggle learning it later. Irony is that I actually got criticized for not knowing any Spanish. I couldn't grip the language in high school and was further criticized for not listening to my culture's music. My question was: How could I connect to music tied to a culture whose people constantly beat me down and had high expectations? I never really had a taste in music until high school where I discovered rock and metal. From themes of telling people to get out of your face to dealing with inner demons, this genre got me through a lot. I didn't care what was popular. I found what spoke to me and had entertainment value. This movie seems to intend on hitting a subject a lot of people can relate to.

text: I saw the film tonight at a preview screening at CAAMfest 2019 (the International Asian American Film Festival in San Francisco, California). The film was a-w-e-s-o-m-e with music of the times (late 80's) but mostly Bruce Springsteen songs. The director, writer, producer of the film Gurinder Chadha was here in the house to do questions and answers. She said she got the author of the original book to work with her to write the screenplay for this film. Chadha also met Bruce Springsteen and spoke with him about the movie and screenplay and he gave the story his approval himself.  I laughed and cried and tapped my feet during this film. I loved how the Boss's music was integrated into the story. Almost everyone will identify with feeling estranged from parents while growing up and struggling to find your way while dealing with pressure from parents. I hope everyone who loves heartwarming stories and excellent film-making will come out and see this film!! It'll be coming out in a few months...

text: I'm a Caribbean Latina who was born to a white Cuban mother and  Afro-Puerto Rican father, and I have always preferred k-pop/j-pop, electronic music, soft rock, and certain alternative kinds of songs to reggaeton or any similar sounding music any fellow latino youth generally listened to. I always found the lyrics to some of the Asian songs I heard from animes poetic and meaningful, and I also appreciated the messages behind the alternative songs I found on YouTube as a teenager. Although I grew up in a fully Hispanic culture, the one musician that has always spoken to me is Owl City, abstract as his music may seem. Although most people do not appear to understand his music or the meaning behind it, his songs are ethereal and every lyric he has written makes perfect sense to me and has helped me through some of the toughest times in my life.

text: Finally saw this movie tonight. Very much enjoyed it. Nice acting. Important to look at a situation from a different point of view. To put yourself in the shoes of a family coming to a new land.There is adjustment to a different culture, made all the more poignant by a generation gap, the inevitable cruelty to anyone ‚Äòdifferent‚Äô, and a young man caught in the middle of it all, who finds the songs of a certain musician helping him believe in himself, and follow his dreams. A little campy, corny? For sure, and corny is good in ‚Äò Blinded By The Light‚Äô. We could use some good, down to earth, story telling these days. Thank you for allowing this movie to get made. August 21, 2019.

text: Don‚Äôt let the score on rotten tomatoes fool you, this movie is insufferable. I almost walked out of the cinema from being uncomfortable and bored. Imagine Billy Elliot with clumsy direction, poor and cringy dialogue and unlikable main characters. It‚Äôs literally Billy Elliot, but pakistani. I feel bad for Pakistan for this monstrosity of a snooze fest. The main character is literally a 16 year old who listens to Bruce Springsteen once, and then makes his entire personality about worshipping the singer. The movie brings nothing new to the table at all, many of the scenes are pointless. I feel bad for the actor, but most of the time I wanted to smack the main character‚Äôs stupid smile off his face. Really? You get a girlfriend and you decide to literally sing lyrics who someone else wrote to her face instead of talking to her? That aspect of his obsession with Springsteen reminded me of the Rose Byrne movie ‚ÄúJuliet, naked‚Äù. I‚Äôd recommend watching that movie instead of this garbage.
